Task 3: Learn 6 Crucial Terraform Terminologies

1. Provider: A plugin that terraform uses to communicate with platforms. 
Eg: AWS provider is used by terrform to create EC2

2. Resource: Infrastructure structure managed by terraform like VM, storage bucket, DB and networks
eg: "Create an S3 bucket named company-backups as a Terraform resource."

3. State: terraform record of its maintained infrastructure, it keeps info about existing infrastructure so it knows what is created and needs to be changed.
eg: "The terraform.tfstate file remembers that the web-server VM already exists."

4. Plan: A plan is a preview of the actions, it will make your infrastructure match your configuration. t shows what will be added, changed, or removed before anything is actually modified.
eg: Terraform plans to create 1 VM, update 1 security group, and delete 1 unused bucket.

5. HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language):
HCL is the human-readable language used to describe infrastructure in Terraform. we write your desired resources and settings in HCL files.
eg: "Write HCL to define an AWS EC2 instance with two CPUs and a specific machine image."

6. Module:
A module is a reusable collection of Terraform configuration that groups related resources together. Instead of rewriting the same infrastructure definitions, you can reuse a module wherever you need it.

